@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Soil Testing Guidance";
}

<h2>@ViewData["Title"]</h2>
<div class="col-md-9">
    <style>
        table { width: 80%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; }
        th, td { border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; }
        th { background-color: #f4f4f4; }
    </style>
    <h4>Importance of Soil Testing</h4>
    <p>It is always beneficial to check the nutrient content of the soil and give the correct amount of fertilizer. Generally, a soil sample can be taken once after three to four years. But if crops are grown two to three times a year, it is necessary to take a soil sample every year. Since the amount of these nutrients changes every year, a soil sample should be taken every year to check the nitrogen content.</p>

    <h4>When to Take Soil Samples</h4>
    <p>Soil samples should be taken in the months of April and May. Soil samples should not be taken within three months of applying organic or chemical fertilizers during the growing season.</p>

    <h4>Soil Sampling Process</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Consider factors like soil color, rockiness, height, and tillage conditions.</li>
        <li>Divide the field into sections of 1/2-2 hectares.</li>
        <li>Take samples from each section, ensuring representation.</li>
        <li>Mark sampling locations with branches or stones.</li>
        <li>Dig pits at the marked locations.</li>
        <li>Remove mulch and weeds before sampling.</li>
        <li>For seasonal crops, dig a 30 cm deep pit; for horticultural crops, dig a 60 cm deep pit.</li>
        <li>Collect and mix soil from 10-12 locations.</li>
        <li>Remove stones and roots, then reduce the sample to about 1 kg.</li>
    </ul>
    <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: row; margin-bottom: 20px">
        <img src="pitposition.png" width="40%" height="40%" style="padding-right: 2rem;"/>
        <img src="partofsoil.jpeg" width="40%" height="40%" style="padding-right: 2rem;"/>
    </div>
    
    <h4>Recommended Pit Depth for Sampling</h4>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Crop Type</th><th>Depth (cm)</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Seasonal Crops</td><td>20-25 cm</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Horticultural Crops</td><td>30-40 cm</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Fruit Crops</td><td>60 cm</td></tr>
    </table>
    <img src="vpit.jpeg" width="60%" height="60%" style="margin-bottom: 20px;"/>
    <h4>Locations to Avoid</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Near water tables</li>
        <li>Swampy areas</li>
        <li>Near homes</li>
        <li>Animal confinement areas</li>
        <li>Manure and waste disposal sites</li>
        <li>Near trees</li>
        <li>Close to farm embankments</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Information to Collect with the Soil Sample</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Sample number</li>
        <li>Date of sampling</li>
        <li>Farmer's address and contact details</li>
        <li>Farm location or survey number</li>
        <li>Sample area (acre/hectare)</li>
        <li>Land slope (flat/sloping)</li>
        <li>Special conditions (saltiness, acidity, etc.)</li>
        <li>Water drainage quality</li>
        <li>Soil depth</li>
        <li>Type of land (horticulture/arable)</li>
        <li>Irrigation method</li>
        <li>Previous crop and yield</li>
        <li>Fertilizers used and quantity</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Factors Analyzed in Soil and Water Testing</h4>
    <h5>Soil</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>pH (Acid-Base Index)</li>
        <li>Alkalinity (Soluble Salts)</li>
        <li>Organic Carbon</li>
        <li>Available nutrients (kg/ha)</li>
        <li>Available energy (kg/ha)</li>
        <li>Available Palash (Km/ha)</li>
        <li>Limestone (%)</li>
        <li>Micronutrients (Fe, Mn, Zn, Cu)</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Water</h5>
    <ul>
        <li>pH (Acid-Base Index)</li>
        <li>Total Soluble Salts</li>
        <li>Calcium (mg equiv/L)</li>
        <li>Magnesium (mg equiv/L)</li>
        <li>Sodium (mg equiv/L)</li>
        <li>Potassium (mg equiv/L)</li>
        <li>Carbonates (mg equiv/L)</li>
        <li>Bicarbonates (mg equiv/L)</li>
        <li>Chlorides (mg equiv/L)</li>
        <li>Sodium Absorption Ratio (SAR)</li>
    </ul>
</div>